WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.338 --> 00:00:04.421
(lighthearted music)

2
00:00:08.820 --> 00:00:10.020
<v David>We're gonna turn our attention</v>

3
00:00:10.020 --> 00:00:12.210
to maternity care too,

4
00:00:12.210 --> 00:00:16.020
and this is a discussion we're gonna have related to kind

5
00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:19.320
of medical issues and intrapartum issues,

6
00:00:19.320 --> 00:00:21.420
and we'll start with this question.

7
00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:24.060
A 32-year-old pregnant woman at 34 weeks comes in

8
00:00:24.060 --> 00:00:26.190
with a blood pressure, systolic blood pressure,

9
00:00:26.190 --> 00:00:29.733
greater than 140, and the diastolic is over 90.

10
00:00:30.570 --> 00:00:32.310
On examination, she's developed edema

11
00:00:32.310 --> 00:00:35.520
in her face and hands along with mild epigastric pain.

12
00:00:35.520 --> 00:00:37.950
Laboratory tests reveal elevated liver enzymes

13
00:00:37.950 --> 00:00:38.850
and thrombocytopenia.

14
00:00:38.850 --> 00:00:42.480
Urinalysis demonstrates a significant presence of protein.

15
00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:44.400
Considering her symptoms and finding,

16
00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:46.620
what specific renal manifestation

17
00:00:46.620 --> 00:00:49.260
would be most indicative of her condition,

18
00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:51.993
distinguishing it from gestational hypertension?

19
00:00:56.970 --> 00:01:00.138
It would be the reduced glomerular filtration rate.

20
00:01:00.138 --> 00:01:00.971
(audience laughing)

21
00:01:00.971 --> 00:01:02.980
So it's a learning opportunity

22
00:01:04.650 --> 00:01:07.080
'cause proteinuria is no longer needed

23
00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:12.000
as a factor in gestational hypertension.

24
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.470
So let's look at the definitions

25
00:01:13.470 --> 00:01:16.020
of hypertensive disorders of pregnancy.

26
00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:18.650
By definition, we define hypertension

27
00:01:18.650 --> 00:01:21.420
as greater than 140 over 90 on two occasions at least.

28
00:01:21.420 --> 00:01:25.563
So four hours apart, or greater than 160 over 110,

29
00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:27.783
either of those.

30
00:01:28.710 --> 00:01:30.210
Now, once we do that,

31
00:01:30.210 --> 00:01:31.890
we gotta figure out what the diagnosis is.

32
00:01:31.890 --> 00:01:34.680
Is it preeclampsia or is it eclampsia?

33
00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:36.390
Is it chronic hypertension?

34
00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:39.390
Is it chronic hypertension with superimposed preeclampsia,

35
00:01:39.390 --> 00:01:42.300
or is it gestational hypertension?

36
00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:44.640
Now, let's take a look at the diagnosis

37
00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:46.680
of preeclampsia and eclampsia.

38
00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:47.820
Key take home.

39
00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:50.853
This does not occur before 20 weeks.

40
00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:54.570
You do not have to have proteinuria as long

41
00:01:54.570 --> 00:01:57.930
as you have one or more of the severe features.

42
00:01:57.930 --> 00:01:59.760
Now, we don't collect 24-hour urines anymore.

43
00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:00.840
It's too cumbersome.

44
00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:02.610
We use a protein to creatinine ratio.

45
00:02:02.610 --> 00:02:06.330
If it's greater than .3, we have significant proteinuria,

46
00:02:06.330 --> 00:02:09.750
or on a dipstick or some other qualitative measure,

47
00:02:09.750 --> 00:02:11.970
I have two plus or more.

48
00:02:11.970 --> 00:02:14.310
Now, what are those severe features

49
00:02:14.310 --> 00:02:16.800
where I don't need proteinuria,

50
00:02:16.800 --> 00:02:19.680
but I still have preeclampsia?

51
00:02:19.680 --> 00:02:22.260
Well, if I got significantly elevated blood pressure,

52
00:02:22.260 --> 00:02:26.700
as we said, greater than 160 over 110, platelet count low,

53
00:02:26.700 --> 00:02:28.410
impaired liver function,

54
00:02:28.410 --> 00:02:32.040
progressive renal insufficiency, pulmonary edema,

55
00:02:32.040 --> 00:02:35.910
new onset headache, which is unresponsive to medication

56
00:02:35.910 --> 00:02:38.820
and visual disturbances, any of those

57
00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:40.800
and the blood pressure, doesn't matter

58
00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:42.870
if I have proteinuria.

59
00:02:42.870 --> 00:02:45.570
Now, patients who have had preeclampsia,

60
00:02:45.570 --> 00:02:47.640
four-times increased risk of hypertension

61
00:02:47.640 --> 00:02:50.850
and a two-times increased risk of ischemic heart disease,

62
00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:54.213
stroke and venous thromboembolic events.

63
00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:58.680
Now, here are the risk factors for preeclampsia.

64
00:02:58.680 --> 00:03:01.770
There are pregnancy associated factors.

65
00:03:01.770 --> 00:03:03.960
There are paternal specific factors,

66
00:03:03.960 --> 00:03:07.260
including, I, myself, was the offspring

67
00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:10.590
of a preeclamptic pregnancy and lastly,

68
00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:12.630
there are maternal specific factors.

69
00:03:12.630 --> 00:03:17.580
Keeping in mind any medical condition increases your risk

70
00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:21.180
for this, and that's where they're gonna go on the exam.

71
00:03:21.180 --> 00:03:23.640
They're gonna tell you they've got diabetes

72
00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:26.283
or renal disease or a thrombophilia.

73
00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:30.120
Now, remember, eclampsia is where I have a seizure

74
00:03:30.120 --> 00:03:31.803
on top of the preeclampsia.

75
00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:36.360
Chronic hypertension is the third issue.

76
00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:39.210
This is where I have a gestational blood pressure elevation,

77
00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:42.093
but it's before the 20th week.

78
00:03:43.980 --> 00:03:46.650
Chronic hypertension is the most common cause

79
00:03:46.650 --> 00:03:49.110
of intrauterine growth restriction.

80
00:03:49.110 --> 00:03:51.660
Now, a quarter of these women are going

81
00:03:51.660 --> 00:03:53.430
to develop the fourth issue,

82
00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:55.200
in terms of hypertensive disorder,

83
00:03:55.200 --> 00:03:57.630
where I develop preeclampsia on top

84
00:03:57.630 --> 00:04:00.990
of my chronic hypertension.

85
00:04:00.990 --> 00:04:03.720
So normally, when you're pregnant,

86
00:04:03.720 --> 00:04:06.900
whether you're hypertensive or not hypertensive,

87
00:04:06.900 --> 00:04:08.730
as you move into the second trimester,

88
00:04:08.730 --> 00:04:10.743
you see a fall in the blood pressure.

89
00:04:12.570 --> 00:04:14.430
Well, if you have chronic hypertension, you're gonna see

90
00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:17.940
that fall and then all of a sudden, it starts going up.

91
00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:18.773
Is it going up

92
00:04:18.773 --> 00:04:21.360
because their chronic hypertension's getting worse,

93
00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:25.023
or they're developing superimposed preeclampsia?

94
00:04:26.460 --> 00:04:29.010
That's where the lab can come in to help

95
00:04:29.010 --> 00:04:32.130
because if you have chronic hypertension,

96
00:04:32.130 --> 00:04:33.660
your uric acid will be normal.

97
00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:35.250
You won't have hemoconcentration.

98
00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:37.710
You won't have abnormal liver function tests.

99
00:04:37.710 --> 00:04:40.860
You shouldn't have an elevated protein and creatinine ratio

100
00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:43.140
or 24-hour total urine protein,

101
00:04:43.140 --> 00:04:47.010
if that's the way you're looking at it, okay?

102
00:04:47.010 --> 00:04:49.260
So you never want to just increase

103
00:04:49.260 --> 00:04:52.110
the blood pressure medication in a chronic hypertensive

104
00:04:52.110 --> 00:04:54.930
as it's going up because you could be masking

105
00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:56.853
their preeclampsia developing.

106
00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:01.620
How do we manage this?

107
00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:04.590
Here's April of 2022-ACOG.

108
00:05:05.550 --> 00:05:09.540
We used to use 160 over 110 as the threshold

109
00:05:09.540 --> 00:05:11.840
for lowering blood pressure in pregnant women.

110
00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:18.650
More recent data suggests we should use 140 over 90.

111
00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:22.920
What this chap study did not show,

112
00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:26.130
which is the chap stands for chronic hypertension

113
00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:30.033
in pregnancy, is where do we need to get to?

114
00:05:31.020 --> 00:05:32.763
Where do we need to get to?

115
00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:37.530
However, we no longer use the threshold

116
00:05:37.530 --> 00:05:40.680
of greater than 160 over 110 to treat.

117
00:05:40.680 --> 00:05:43.470
We now use the threshold of over 140 over 90.

118
00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:44.910
Some of some of you're thinking, well,

119
00:05:44.910 --> 00:05:47.610
why would it we have ever used a different threshold?

120
00:05:47.610 --> 00:05:50.040
Because remember, we manage chronic hypertension

121
00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:53.883
in a non-pregnant patient to minimize long-term sequelae.

122
00:05:54.870 --> 00:05:57.390
Day-to-day, it doesn't make any difference.

123
00:05:57.390 --> 00:06:00.060
However, here we recently have learned

124
00:06:00.060 --> 00:06:02.880
that perhaps this could have an impact on management

125
00:06:02.880 --> 00:06:06.630
of the pregnancy, even though it's nine months, okay?

126
00:06:06.630 --> 00:06:09.450
Blood pressure medications at the start of the pregnancy,

127
00:06:09.450 --> 00:06:10.860
they can be maintained on them

128
00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:14.673
with the exception of ACEs or ARBs.

129
00:06:17.970 --> 00:06:19.680
If we look at the American College of Cardiology

130
00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:22.980
and the American Heart Association way back in 2014,

131
00:06:22.980 --> 00:06:26.790
they recommend either methyldopa, labetalol or nifedipine.

132
00:06:26.790 --> 00:06:28.680
Most people use labetalol now.

133
00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:30.150
So I had a patient come in not too long ago.

134
00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:34.470
She's trying to get pregnant, trying to get pregnant,

135
00:06:34.470 --> 00:06:38.370
and she had recently seen her obstetrician gynecologist,

136
00:06:38.370 --> 00:06:39.720
I'm not doing her prenatal care,

137
00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:43.323
and they kept her on her ACE inhibitor.

138
00:06:46.470 --> 00:06:48.810
I'm like, "Are you trying to get pregnant?"

139
00:06:48.810 --> 00:06:51.450
She said, "Yeah, I came off of my birth control."

140
00:06:51.450 --> 00:06:52.717
The obstetrician gynecologist said,

141
00:06:52.717 --> 00:06:53.760
"Okay, we're gonna stop it."

142
00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:55.110
I'm like, "Did they know you're on an ACE?"

143
00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:57.450
She said, "Yeah, they looked at all my medications."

144
00:06:57.450 --> 00:06:59.970
I'm like, "We're gonna stop that today,"

145
00:06:59.970 --> 00:07:01.890
and we put her on labetalol.

146
00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:06.210
Okay, after giving birth, you may need to continue these.

147
00:07:06.210 --> 00:07:10.083
Now, we now have a way of preventing preeclampsia.

148
00:07:11.730 --> 00:07:14.970
So we start everybody at about 12 weeks who has a history

149
00:07:14.970 --> 00:07:17.490
of preeclampsia, or they're at high risk

150
00:07:17.490 --> 00:07:22.473
on low-dose aspirin, and you continue that through delivery.

151
00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:25.320
Continue that through delivery.

152
00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:29.220
Here's what the USPSTF says in terms of high risk,

153
00:07:29.220 --> 00:07:31.320
and therefore, you need aspirin.

154
00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:33.840
History of preeclampsia, multi-fetal gestation,

155
00:07:33.840 --> 00:07:36.420
chronic hypertension, diabetes, renal disease

156
00:07:36.420 --> 00:07:39.380
or an autoimmune disease, okay?

157
00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:41.970
12 weeks, and we continue it through the end of pregnancy.

158
00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:43.590
Now, gestational hypertension,

159
00:07:43.590 --> 00:07:46.710
which accounts for the last two types.

160
00:07:46.710 --> 00:07:49.803
I've got blood pressure rise after 20 weeks.

161
00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:53.220
So I'm worried about preeclampsia,

162
00:07:53.220 --> 00:07:55.680
but I never develop a severe feature,

163
00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:57.663
and I never get proteinuria.

164
00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:03.000
We can further delineate this after they deliver at 12 weeks

165
00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:04.080
because if it goes to normal,

166
00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:06.270
they had transient hypertension of pregnancy.

167
00:08:06.270 --> 00:08:09.090
If it doesn't, they've got chronic hypertension.

168
00:08:09.090 --> 00:08:10.893
The timing of delivery here.

169
00:08:11.850 --> 00:08:14.520
Gestational hypertension or preeclampsia

170
00:08:14.520 --> 00:08:16.380
without severe features, you want to get 'em

171
00:08:16.380 --> 00:08:18.033
to 37 weeks and deliver 'em.

172
00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:21.180
Women with chronic hypertension,

173
00:08:21.180 --> 00:08:24.540
no additional maternal or fetal complications.

174
00:08:24.540 --> 00:08:27.330
IE, something that says you need earlier delivery.

175
00:08:27.330 --> 00:08:30.510
If they've not been prescribed hypertensive medications

176
00:08:30.510 --> 00:08:32.640
because they have been persistently less than 140

177
00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:35.850
over 90, you deliver by 38 weeks.

178
00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:39.183
If they're on medication, you deliver by 37 weeks.

179
00:08:41.880 --> 00:08:44.170
Here is just a summary of that

180
00:08:45.990 --> 00:08:49.620
in terms of our recommendation.

181
00:08:49.620 --> 00:08:51.510
So you can put that with your study materials.

182
00:08:51.510 --> 00:08:53.580
Now, how do we manage eclampsia

183
00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:55.200
and the potential for eclampsia?

184
00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:57.570
Well, we give 'em anticonvulsive therapy.

185
00:08:57.570 --> 00:08:59.280
Magnesium sulfate is used both

186
00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:04.280
for prevention and for treatment.

187
00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:06.930
Now, it's only recommended

188
00:09:06.930 --> 00:09:09.330
for prevention if you have preeclampsia

189
00:09:09.330 --> 00:09:10.593
with severe features.

190
00:09:11.970 --> 00:09:13.620
Now, you can use it with mild to moderate,

191
00:09:13.620 --> 00:09:16.590
but it's only recommended for severe features.

192
00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:18.540
It reduces the risk of subsequent seizures

193
00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:20.970
in women who already have eclampsia.

194
00:09:20.970 --> 00:09:24.750
That antidote for the toxicity is calcium gluconate.

195
00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:26.040
You treat their blood pressure.

196
00:09:26.040 --> 00:09:29.220
Here, a vaginal delivery is preferred

197
00:09:29.220 --> 00:09:31.440
because many of these women will develop DIC,

198
00:09:31.440 --> 00:09:34.230
and that's the last patient you wanna be operating on.

199
00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:36.390
Now, sometimes you can have an eclamptic pregnancy.

200
00:09:36.390 --> 00:09:39.753
I remember one very specifically eclamptic.

201
00:09:41.790 --> 00:09:44.040
Everything settled down.

202
00:09:44.040 --> 00:09:45.870
Induced her, got her to fully dilate,

203
00:09:45.870 --> 00:09:47.940
and then, of course, she couldn't push the baby out.

204
00:09:47.940 --> 00:09:50.310
Had to do a forcep delivery,

205
00:09:50.310 --> 00:09:52.117
and I remember thinking,

206
00:09:52.117 --> 00:09:54.180
"I better not put a stitch too deep here"

207
00:09:54.180 --> 00:09:56.910
'cause she had this enormous tear up into the sulcus,

208
00:09:56.910 --> 00:09:59.010
and I'm like, "I better not put a stitch in too deep here

209
00:09:59.010 --> 00:10:01.260
'cause I'll be in the bladder."

210
00:10:01.260 --> 00:10:04.050
She'd probably been better off with the cesarean section.

211
00:10:04.050 --> 00:10:07.080
Okay, she's step right over here.

212
00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:08.550
She's still with that furrowed brow.

213
00:10:08.550 --> 00:10:10.890
She's like, "Oh, my gosh." (laughs)

214
00:10:10.890 --> 00:10:14.730
Okay, acute hypertension in preeclampsia.

215
00:10:14.730 --> 00:10:17.790
Definitely if it's greater than 160 over 110 intrapartum,

216
00:10:17.790 --> 00:10:18.750
you want to treat that,

217
00:10:18.750 --> 00:10:22.020
and we wanna get it down to below 140 over 90.

218
00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:24.060
Beta blockers are what we normally reach for.

219
00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:24.893
Look at this, though.

220
00:10:24.893 --> 00:10:29.203
Calcium antagonist giving a dose of nifedipine PO.

221
00:10:30.360 --> 00:10:34.320
Actually works faster than labetalol IV, hmm?

222
00:10:34.320 --> 00:10:36.540
Okay, postpartum.

223
00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:39.240
I'm gonna reevaluate them at 7 to 10 days

224
00:10:39.240 --> 00:10:42.150
and then reevaluate them at 12 weeks

225
00:10:42.150 --> 00:10:45.540
to determine do I need to continue blood pressure medication

226
00:10:45.540 --> 00:10:47.590
for persistently elevated blood pressure?

227
00:10:48.990 --> 00:10:50.070
30-year-old woman known

228
00:10:50.070 --> 00:10:51.990
to have preexisting type two diabetes presents

229
00:10:51.990 --> 00:10:55.260
for her regular antenatal checkup at 32 weeks gestation.

230
00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:56.940
Her glucose control has been variable

231
00:10:56.940 --> 00:10:58.290
despite rigorous management.

232
00:10:58.290 --> 00:11:00.000
The ultrasound reveals a fetus

233
00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:01.140
with an abdominal circumference

234
00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:03.090
measuring greater than 95th percentile

235
00:11:03.090 --> 00:11:05.010
for gestational age.

236
00:11:05.010 --> 00:11:06.710
The mother's hemoglobin A1C levels

237
00:11:07.620 --> 00:11:11.493
have been consistently elevated throughout her pregnancy.

238
00:11:14.130 --> 00:11:15.600
Considering her medical history

239
00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:17.340
and the fetal ultrasound findings,

240
00:11:17.340 --> 00:11:20.940
which perinatal complication is most likely attributed

241
00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:23.940
to the fetal exposure to maternal hyperglycemia

242
00:11:23.940 --> 00:11:25.230
in this scenario?

243
00:11:25.230 --> 00:11:27.870
Is it RDS, neural tube defect,

244
00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:30.363
intrauterine growth restriction or macrosomia?

245
00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:37.500
Good, there we go.

246
00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:41.940
Macrosomia, which is by definition greater than 4,500 grams.

247
00:11:41.940 --> 00:11:44.670
Keeping in mind, do you know what the best estimate

248
00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:46.920
or how you determine the best estimate

249
00:11:46.920 --> 00:11:49.320
of fetal weight at term?

250
00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:50.283
Any ideas?

251
00:11:51.317 --> 00:11:52.530
<v ->Ultrasound.</v>
<v ->Ultrasound.</v>

252
00:11:52.530 --> 00:11:55.620
<v David>Ultrasound is the least accurate.</v>

253
00:11:55.620 --> 00:11:58.920
It'll be off by as much as 20%.

254
00:11:58.920 --> 00:12:00.270
Leopold's, I heard.

255
00:12:00.270 --> 00:12:01.890
That's the second most accurate.

256
00:12:01.890 --> 00:12:04.380
That's where I feel the mother's abdomen.

257
00:12:04.380 --> 00:12:06.330
The most accurate way hands down,

258
00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:09.753
has been shown over and over and every study ever published.

259
00:12:10.669 --> 00:12:11.502
(audience chattering)

260
00:12:11.502 --> 00:12:14.838
You ask the mother how much do you think the baby weighs?

261
00:12:14.838 --> 00:12:16.050
(audience laughing)

262
00:12:16.050 --> 00:12:19.080
That is the most accurate predictor

263
00:12:19.080 --> 00:12:21.633
of the fetal weight at term.

264
00:12:22.470 --> 00:12:23.673
Amazing, isn't it?

265
00:12:24.720 --> 00:12:27.330
Okay, why do we worry about diabetes?

266
00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:28.920
From a maternal standpoint,

267
00:12:28.920 --> 00:12:30.583
hypertensive disorder, cesarean,

268
00:12:30.583 --> 00:12:33.960
because of macrosomia, there's an increased risk

269
00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:36.480
of intrauterine fetal demise,

270
00:12:36.480 --> 00:12:39.060
if there's persistent hyperglycemia,

271
00:12:39.060 --> 00:12:40.590
particularly fasting.

272
00:12:40.590 --> 00:12:41.940
From a fetal standpoint,

273
00:12:41.940 --> 00:12:45.840
excessive fetal growth and ounce for ounce,

274
00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:48.750
if you have an infant of a diabetic mother,

275
00:12:48.750 --> 00:12:51.540
you will see a broader bisacromial

276
00:12:51.540 --> 00:12:53.730
or shoulder diameter in the infant

277
00:12:53.730 --> 00:12:55.470
of the diabetic mother than you do

278
00:12:55.470 --> 00:12:58.020
in the infant of a non-diabetic mother.

279
00:12:58.020 --> 00:13:01.710
So 4,000 grams, the baby is architecturally

280
00:13:01.710 --> 00:13:03.810
looking different in an infant

281
00:13:03.810 --> 00:13:05.490
of a diabetic mother than the infant

282
00:13:05.490 --> 00:13:07.560
of a non-diabetic mother,

283
00:13:07.560 --> 00:13:10.620
and then there's neonatal morbidity, hypoglycemia,

284
00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:14.880
hypocalcemia, hyperbilirubinemia and polycythemia.

285
00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:16.440
Now, we initially manage this

286
00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:18.993
with nutrition and physical activity.

287
00:13:20.970 --> 00:13:23.250
What's the threshold at which we have to start treatment?

288
00:13:23.250 --> 00:13:25.560
We don't really know.

289
00:13:25.560 --> 00:13:30.243
When we do start treatment, insulin is first line.

290
00:13:31.174 --> 00:13:33.757
Glyburide, not recommended.

291
00:13:33.757 --> 00:13:36.660
"Well, Dr. Weismiller, I am not going on insulin,

292
00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:39.240
or I don't think I can take this,"

293
00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:43.203
then metformin is the second-line drug.

294
00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:46.530
We don't know exactly when to start.

295
00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:51.530
However, what we're going for are fastings less than 95

296
00:13:51.720 --> 00:13:53.793
and two-hour postprandial less than 120.

297
00:13:55.020 --> 00:13:57.450
If on more than three occasions you exceed this,

298
00:13:57.450 --> 00:14:00.060
you should start insulin therapy.

299
00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:05.060
In our practice, we really focus on the fasting blood sugar

300
00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:08.910
because we know that the persistent fasting hyperglycemia

301
00:14:08.910 --> 00:14:11.400
leads to most of the poor outcomes.

302
00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:13.470
So in my patients,

303
00:14:13.470 --> 00:14:17.040
if the fasting is less than 95 every single day,

304
00:14:17.040 --> 00:14:19.560
and she's occasionally bumping around at 130

305
00:14:19.560 --> 00:14:22.053
or 140 postprandial, I don't start insulin.

306
00:14:23.490 --> 00:14:25.350
Okay, now, what about the delivery?

307
00:14:25.350 --> 00:14:27.360
Controlled, and I'm an A1.

308
00:14:27.360 --> 00:14:29.400
That is, by definition,

309
00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:31.800
diet and physical activity controlled.

310
00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:36.800
I delivered them at, not before, 39 weeks

311
00:14:36.990 --> 00:14:39.780
and not after 40 and six, seven weeks.

312
00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:41.760
Well controlled, but they're on medication,

313
00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:44.040
I wanna deliver in the 39th week.

314
00:14:44.040 --> 00:14:47.790
Poorly controlled, typically we're delivering

315
00:14:47.790 --> 00:14:49.893
at 37 to 38 weeks.

316
00:14:52.140 --> 00:14:54.600
In a mother who has diabetes,

317
00:14:54.600 --> 00:14:58.200
if the estimated fetal weight is greater than 4,500 grams,

318
00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:00.780
you can consider a primary section.

319
00:15:00.780 --> 00:15:02.643
Rarely is that done.

320
00:15:04.110 --> 00:15:07.200
For a non-diabetic mother, you can consider this

321
00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:10.203
if the estimated fetal weight is greater than 5,000 grams.

322
00:15:11.160 --> 00:15:12.963
Long-term considerations.

323
00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:18.030
Up to 35% of women who have gestational diabetes

324
00:15:18.030 --> 00:15:21.750
will develop diabetes within 5 to 10 years of parturition,

325
00:15:21.750 --> 00:15:24.390
and the infant there is an increased risk for obesity,

326
00:15:24.390 --> 00:15:27.543
glucose intolerance and diabetes in late adolescence.

327
00:15:28.410 --> 00:15:30.720
We wanna reclassify mom preferably

328
00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:33.240
about four weeks postpartum,

329
00:15:33.240 --> 00:15:35.160
using either a fasting plasma glucose

330
00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:37.083
or a two-hour glucose tolerance test.

331
00:15:38.250 --> 00:15:41.550
If that is normal, the recommendation is

332
00:15:41.550 --> 00:15:44.500
to reevaluate that annually per the USPSTF

333
00:15:46.200 --> 00:15:48.153
or every three years per the ADA.

334
00:15:50.460 --> 00:15:55.460
26-year-old G2P1 presents at 30 weeks, severe itching.

335
00:15:56.130 --> 00:15:58.440
She has excoriations from scratching in various areas.

336
00:15:58.440 --> 00:16:00.000
She says that she had the same problem

337
00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:01.413
during the last pregnancy.

338
00:16:02.610 --> 00:16:04.950
You review her medical records and see she had a diagnosis

339
00:16:04.950 --> 00:16:07.173
of intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy.

340
00:16:08.310 --> 00:16:09.840
Elevation of which of the following

341
00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:12.540
is the most characteristic of this disorder?

342
00:16:12.540 --> 00:16:16.080
Serum GGT, serum bile acids, serum unconjugated bilirubin

343
00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:19.350
or a prothrombin time.

344
00:16:19.350 --> 00:16:22.053
Which of those is most characteristic?

345
00:16:27.180 --> 00:16:29.460
Okay, serum bile acids.

346
00:16:29.460 --> 00:16:31.230
Some of you're thinking now how would I order that?

347
00:16:31.230 --> 00:16:32.520
You just go into your order set

348
00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:33.810
and look for serum bile acids.

349
00:16:33.810 --> 00:16:35.850
It's right there. Promise you.

350
00:16:35.850 --> 00:16:36.683
Promise you.

351
00:16:36.683 --> 00:16:39.690
Okay, now if we think about this,

352
00:16:39.690 --> 00:16:42.630
it's the most common pregnancy related liver disorder,

353
00:16:42.630 --> 00:16:44.223
although it is not common.

354
00:16:46.050 --> 00:16:47.730
We don't know really what causes this.

355
00:16:47.730 --> 00:16:49.503
We just know it tends to recur.

356
00:16:51.120 --> 00:16:53.433
Historically, they will itch at night,

357
00:16:54.330 --> 00:16:59.330
then they'll itch continually, and there's no rash.

358
00:16:59.820 --> 00:17:02.610
About a half of them will develop jaundice.

359
00:17:02.610 --> 00:17:05.163
Rarely do you see this early in pregnancy.

360
00:17:06.330 --> 00:17:08.250
More than 20% of women are known

361
00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:10.863
to be infected with hepatitis C will develop this.

362
00:17:11.730 --> 00:17:12.870
Therefore, you should screen

363
00:17:12.870 --> 00:17:15.420
for hep C in patients who have this.

364
00:17:15.420 --> 00:17:17.670
Liver biopsy is rarely going to be needed.

365
00:17:17.670 --> 00:17:19.920
What you're looking for is a serum bile acid

366
00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:22.833
greater than three times the upper limits of normal,

367
00:17:24.090 --> 00:17:25.740
and in terms of treatment, you only have

368
00:17:25.740 --> 00:17:28.470
to worry about one drug, ursodeoxycholic acid

369
00:17:28.470 --> 00:17:31.923
because this is the only drug that benefits the infant.

370
00:17:34.740 --> 00:17:38.790
Mom, you will see a decreased pruritus

371
00:17:38.790 --> 00:17:40.770
and a decrease in the bile acids,

372
00:17:40.770 --> 00:17:42.750
but you improve the fetal outcome for the baby

373
00:17:42.750 --> 00:17:45.990
because in the baby, you've got a serious issue here

374
00:17:45.990 --> 00:17:47.400
in terms of fetal compromise.

375
00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:48.930
There's an increased risk of cesarean.

376
00:17:48.930 --> 00:17:50.730
There's an increased risk of meconium.

377
00:17:50.730 --> 00:17:54.150
There's an increased risk of intrauterine fetal demise.

378
00:17:54.150 --> 00:17:55.050
Not a small issue,

379
00:17:55.050 --> 00:17:57.450
but for mom it is an impaired quality of life,

380
00:17:57.450 --> 00:18:00.573
and it will resolve as soon as she delivers.

381
00:18:02.140 --> 00:18:03.600
Okay, bleeding late in the pregnancy.

382
00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:05.340
The two things we need to remind ourselves

383
00:18:05.340 --> 00:18:09.570
of are placenta previa and placental abruption.

384
00:18:09.570 --> 00:18:10.680
Now, here's the question.

385
00:18:10.680 --> 00:18:13.050
A 28-year-old woman at 34 weeks arrives

386
00:18:13.050 --> 00:18:14.370
at the maternity unit.

387
00:18:14.370 --> 00:18:17.310
She's got significant vaginal bleeding.

388
00:18:17.310 --> 00:18:18.750
No associated pain or discomfort.

389
00:18:18.750 --> 00:18:20.460
The bleeding is moderate on exam,

390
00:18:20.460 --> 00:18:22.353
and the fetal heart rate is stable.

391
00:18:23.580 --> 00:18:25.530
Which of the following conditions is most likely

392
00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:29.340
to result in painless vaginal bleeding in late pregnancy?

393
00:18:29.340 --> 00:18:32.613
Cervical polyp, abruption, previa or cervicitis?

394
00:18:37.650 --> 00:18:42.510
Okay, and it is placenta previa, placenta previa.

395
00:18:42.510 --> 00:18:43.770
Let's talk about that.

396
00:18:43.770 --> 00:18:45.753
So now we have a placenta,

397
00:18:47.160 --> 00:18:50.400
which is not optimally positioned

398
00:18:50.400 --> 00:18:53.403
and covering part or all of the cervix.

399
00:18:54.480 --> 00:18:56.670
Now, keeping in mind that

400
00:18:56.670 --> 00:18:59.130
as they have painless vaginal bleeding,

401
00:18:59.130 --> 00:19:01.953
each successive episode becomes more.

402
00:19:03.450 --> 00:19:06.360
Now, the etiology, typically we don't find one.

403
00:19:06.360 --> 00:19:08.310
However, here are the risks.

404
00:19:08.310 --> 00:19:11.763
Anything that has damaged the myo or endometrium.

405
00:19:13.050 --> 00:19:14.880
As Dr. Fernhaber pointed out,

406
00:19:14.880 --> 00:19:18.270
cocaine is not good for many things,

407
00:19:18.270 --> 00:19:22.953
advanced maternal age and tobacco.

408
00:19:24.420 --> 00:19:27.510
Malpresentation is the result, not the cause of this,

409
00:19:27.510 --> 00:19:29.373
and it tends to recur.

410
00:19:30.600 --> 00:19:34.410
Now, before 24 weeks, we just have expected management.

411
00:19:34.410 --> 00:19:36.870
Now, I say here, you will need

412
00:19:36.870 --> 00:19:38.610
to confirm movement of the placenta.

413
00:19:38.610 --> 00:19:41.151
The placenta does not have feet.

414
00:19:41.151 --> 00:19:42.000
(audience laughing)

415
00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:45.180
However, think about the uterus as a balloon,

416
00:19:45.180 --> 00:19:46.860
and you put a mark on a balloon.

417
00:19:46.860 --> 00:19:49.770
As you blow up the balloon, there's relative migration

418
00:19:49.770 --> 00:19:52.950
of the superior and inferior pole.

419
00:19:52.950 --> 00:19:55.650
If it is not cleared by 24 weeks, it's unlikely,

420
00:19:55.650 --> 00:19:59.040
and that patient's most likely going to need a cesarean.

421
00:19:59.040 --> 00:20:01.950
Placental abruption, what's the key here?

422
00:20:01.950 --> 00:20:04.080
High rates of recurrence.

423
00:20:04.080 --> 00:20:08.043
It is a clinical diagnosis.

424
00:20:09.600 --> 00:20:13.950
Abdominal pain and bleeding and no other cause,

425
00:20:13.950 --> 00:20:16.830
you don't care what the ultrasound shows.

426
00:20:16.830 --> 00:20:20.763
They have an abruption until proven otherwise.

427
00:20:21.630 --> 00:20:25.230
Etiology, again, cocaine,

428
00:20:25.230 --> 00:20:28.263
hypertensive disorders, tobacco.

429
00:20:29.790 --> 00:20:33.180
With an abruption, you're assessing fetal viability.

430
00:20:33.180 --> 00:20:34.800
If there's been demise, IE,

431
00:20:34.800 --> 00:20:37.560
you've got more than a 50% detachment.

432
00:20:37.560 --> 00:20:38.790
You deliver the fetus,

433
00:20:38.790 --> 00:20:40.980
and you're gonna prepare to transfuse mom.

434
00:20:40.980 --> 00:20:43.680
If there's a live fetus and a rigid uterus,

435
00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:45.990
again, greater than 50% of detachment,

436
00:20:45.990 --> 00:20:47.940
very high rates of demise.

437
00:20:47.940 --> 00:20:49.410
Live fetus in a soft uterus,

438
00:20:49.410 --> 00:20:51.810
you can probably proceed with induction, okay?

439
00:20:51.810 --> 00:20:55.110
Now, remember, the third stage of labor

440
00:20:55.110 --> 00:20:56.400
between delivery of the baby

441
00:20:56.400 --> 00:20:58.110
and the delivery of the placenta,

442
00:20:58.110 --> 00:21:00.630
that is a massive abruption.

443
00:21:00.630 --> 00:21:03.273
That's how the placenta is delivered.

444
00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:07.260
Okay, here's our antepartum hemorrhage,

445
00:21:07.260 --> 00:21:09.390
previa versus abruption in your study materials.

446
00:21:09.390 --> 00:21:10.503
Preterm labor.

447
00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:13.920
I'm more than 24 weeks, and I'm less than 37 weeks.

448
00:21:13.920 --> 00:21:16.623
I'm contracting, and I got cervical change.

449
00:21:19.500 --> 00:21:22.020
Now, here are the risk factors.

450
00:21:22.020 --> 00:21:24.153
It's happened before.

451
00:21:25.320 --> 00:21:28.890
Any question on the exam where they start

452
00:21:28.890 --> 00:21:33.890
with G2P1 with a history of, it's gonna happen again.

453
00:21:35.370 --> 00:21:38.407
I've had residents call me at three in the morning,

454
00:21:38.407 --> 00:21:42.930
"Dr. Weismiller, 28-weeker here, yada, yada,"

455
00:21:42.930 --> 00:21:46.194
and then they go into what she had for dinner,

456
00:21:46.194 --> 00:21:47.027
(audience laughing)

457
00:21:47.027 --> 00:21:49.200
where she lives.

458
00:21:49.200 --> 00:21:51.600
Is she safe?

459
00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:55.020
And I'm thinking, is she contracting

460
00:21:55.020 --> 00:21:56.970
and is there a history of preterm labor?

461
00:21:56.970 --> 00:22:00.363
Because if she is, I'm on my way now.

462
00:22:01.560 --> 00:22:03.750
We can learn about everything else later.

463
00:22:03.750 --> 00:22:04.650
It's important.

464
00:22:04.650 --> 00:22:06.540
Don't get me wrong.

465
00:22:06.540 --> 00:22:07.650
Sometimes they forget

466
00:22:07.650 --> 00:22:09.910
to tell me whether she's term or preterm

467
00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:12.810
because if she's term, great,

468
00:22:12.810 --> 00:22:15.330
let's go ahead and talk about this,

469
00:22:15.330 --> 00:22:18.150
but if she's preterm, I'm on my way

470
00:22:18.150 --> 00:22:19.800
'cause they're at increased risk.

471
00:22:20.760 --> 00:22:23.370
Lots of babies in there are short cervical length,

472
00:22:23.370 --> 00:22:24.900
when you're evaluating the cervix

473
00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:27.090
between 18 and 25 weeks.

474
00:22:27.090 --> 00:22:28.620
They give you somebody at 30 weeks

475
00:22:28.620 --> 00:22:31.503
with a short cervical length, that doesn't mean anything.

476
00:22:32.670 --> 00:22:36.480
Interpregnancy interval is short, tobacco and any infection.

477
00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:38.430
Okay, here's the symptomatic management.

478
00:22:38.430 --> 00:22:41.700
Activity restriction preterm labor, no benefit.

479
00:22:41.700 --> 00:22:44.100
Hydration, no benefit.

480
00:22:44.100 --> 00:22:46.200
Tocolytic agents, the first line agent

481
00:22:46.200 --> 00:22:49.350
is a beta adrenergic agonist.

482
00:22:49.350 --> 00:22:52.200
It doesn't help you with the exception

483
00:22:52.200 --> 00:22:54.510
of prolonging the pregnancy long enough

484
00:22:54.510 --> 00:22:56.730
to get the thing on board that does help you,

485
00:22:56.730 --> 00:22:58.410
which is corticosteroids.

486
00:22:58.410 --> 00:23:00.797
You get one dose between 24

487
00:23:00.797 --> 00:23:04.140
and 34 weeks if you're at increased risk.

488
00:23:04.140 --> 00:23:06.690
Antibiotics in terms of prolonging the pregnancy

489
00:23:06.690 --> 00:23:09.993
are only helpful if you've got ruptured membranes.

490
00:23:10.920 --> 00:23:14.550
If the membranes are intact, and she's preterm,

491
00:23:14.550 --> 00:23:16.740
and you don't know what her GBS status is,

492
00:23:16.740 --> 00:23:19.200
then, of course, she gets GBS prophylaxis

493
00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:21.030
'cause she's in a high risk group,

494
00:23:21.030 --> 00:23:23.310
but that doesn't prolong the pregnancy.

495
00:23:23.310 --> 00:23:27.720
Magnesium sulfate reduces the risk and severity of CP,

496
00:23:27.720 --> 00:23:30.633
if they're gonna deliver potentially before 32 weeks.

497
00:23:32.610 --> 00:23:37.500
In terms of prevention, you know we've had a lot on this.

498
00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:41.760
For a while, we gave 17-alpha-hydroxyprogesterone caprate.

499
00:23:41.760 --> 00:23:45.690
That is not recommended for primary prevention any longer.

500
00:23:45.690 --> 00:23:48.060
If you're going to look at a single pregnancy

501
00:23:48.060 --> 00:23:51.300
with no prior preterm birth, the only thing you can do is

502
00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:56.300
to look at cervical length between 18 and 22 weeks.

503
00:23:56.700 --> 00:23:59.520
If there is a prior preterm birth,

504
00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:01.620
and there's a short cervical length,

505
00:24:01.620 --> 00:24:05.340
these patients may benefit from micronized progesterone

506
00:24:05.340 --> 00:24:07.443
and a cerclage placement.

507
00:24:08.700 --> 00:24:10.560
I don't think that's gonna be on the exam.

508
00:24:10.560 --> 00:24:12.180
Okay, here's our next question.

509
00:24:12.180 --> 00:24:14.160
26-year-old gravida three para two,

510
00:24:14.160 --> 00:24:15.990
mild chronic hypertension.

511
00:24:15.990 --> 00:24:18.300
Uncomplicated pregnancy has just delivered

512
00:24:18.300 --> 00:24:22.590
a vigorous female by spontaneous vaginal delivery.

513
00:24:22.590 --> 00:24:25.050
She's noted to have heavy vaginal bleeding,

514
00:24:25.050 --> 00:24:27.660
and a bimanual exam reveals a soft,

515
00:24:27.660 --> 00:24:29.580
poorly contracted uterus.

516
00:24:29.580 --> 00:24:33.510
Her temp is 37, blood pressure 168 over 97,

517
00:24:33.510 --> 00:24:38.510
pulse 105, oxygen saturation 95% on room air.

518
00:24:38.970 --> 00:24:41.160
Which one of the following uterotonic agents

519
00:24:41.160 --> 00:24:43.650
is contraindicated in the management

520
00:24:43.650 --> 00:24:46.800
of this patient's postpartum hemorrhage?

521
00:24:46.800 --> 00:24:51.800
Oxytocin, carboprost, misoprostol or methylergonovine.

522
00:24:57.240 --> 00:24:59.640
Okay, good, methylergonovine.

523
00:24:59.640 --> 00:25:03.270
That's gonna drive the blood pressure up even higher.

524
00:25:03.270 --> 00:25:05.970
Now, postpartum hemorrhage,

525
00:25:05.970 --> 00:25:10.500
we have gone through at least 10 definitions

526
00:25:10.500 --> 00:25:13.320
of this since I started practice.

527
00:25:13.320 --> 00:25:18.090
It is now a cumulative blood loss of more than a liter

528
00:25:18.090 --> 00:25:21.180
or blood loss accompanied by signs

529
